Maps of Sri Lanka: http://www.mapsopensource.com/images/sri-lanka-districts-map.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8426568,144

The South Asian COVID-19 situation, according to data from Worldometer (https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/) as of 4 Jun 2021 at 06:06 GMT:

Country: Total cases / Total deaths / Deaths per million population
India: 28 574 350 / 340 719 / 245
Pakistan: 928 588 / 21 105 / 94
Bangladesh: 805 980 / 12 724 / 77
Nepal: 576 936 / 7630 / 258
Sri Lanka: 195 844 / 1608 / 75
Afghanistan: 76 628 / 3068 / 77
Maldives: 66 516 / 173 / 315
Bhutan: 1654 / 1 / 1

Over the last 7 days, 1 026 645, 10 995, 17 286, 34 680, and 5573 COVID-19 cases were detected in India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Nepal, and the Maldives, respectively, compared with 1 515 714, 9791, 17 841, 53 611, and 10 141 in the preceding 7 days, revealing a sharp decreasing trend in India, Nepal, and the Maldives and a slow upward trend again in Bangladesh, but a trend of stability in Pakistan. In Sri Lanka, the curve of the 2nd wave is still growing from the trend of new cases that started creeping up over the last 4 weeks or so; 20 983 new cases were registered in the country over the last 7 days as opposed to 20 075 in the preceding 7 days. The daily number of reported cases in Afghanistan is also increasing, but remains stable at a lower rate in Bhutan, compared with other South Asian countries.

Only time will say whether or not the slow but steady increasing trend of daily case-positivity, as being observed over the last 10 days or so in Bangladesh, would develop a new wave in the country due to detection of the delta variant (previously called B.1.617.2), a variant of concern, in some districts bordering India.

Around 220 million doses of COVID-19 vaccines have been administered in India so far (https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-57354069).

As indicated in item [5D] above, Pakistan has reportedly opened registrations for citizens aged 19 and above for vaccination against COVID-19, expecting an enhancement of vaccine supply in the future. There is no mention, however, in the article of how and when doses of the vaccine required would be made available for them.

To compare the situation in South Asian countries above with previous disease data, ProMED-SoAs readers are referred to the archives below:
